Making of the Macleans 2019 chart

Blake Shaffer

Nov 28, 2018

Data requirements

  • Three files, each with 2 columns (datetime (daily observations) and value)
    1. Coal generation (daily average MWh)
    2. Alberta internal load (daily average MWh)
    3. Alberta hourly average pool price
  • Each was accessed via NRGSTREAM and cannot be posted to github
  • However, each is accessible via aeso.ca to the patient data scraper

1. Begin by calling the necessary libraries

knitr::opts_chunk$set(message=FALSE)
library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
library(ggthemes)
library(scales)
library(grid)
library(gridExtra)
setwd("~/Dropbox/Charts and Data/")

2. Read in the data

filename <- "NRGSTREAM_AB_coal_2000_2018.xlsx"
coal_policy <- readxl::read_xlsx(filename)
coal_policy$datetime <- mdy_hm(coal_policy$datetime)
head(coal_policy)

3. Make the main (large) plot

breaks.index <- seq.POSIXt(from=as.POSIXct(as.Date("2000-01-01"), format="%Y"), to=as.POSIXct(as.Date("2018-12-31"), format="%Y"), by="2 years")
topplot <- ggplot(coal_policy, aes(datetime,value))+
  geom_line(data=coal_policy %>% filter(datetime<ymd("2018-01-01")),color="white")+
  geom_line(data=coal_policy %>% filter(datetime>=ymd("2018-01-01")),color="white")+
  geom_smooth(data=coal_policy %>% filter(datetime<ymd("2018-01-01")),color="#332288",size=1.5)+
  geom_segment(aes(x=as.POSIXct(as.Date("2018-01-01")),
                   xend=as.POSIXct(as.Date("2018-11-08")),
                   y=mean(coal_policy$value[year(coal_policy$datetime)>=2018]),
                   yend=mean(coal_policy$value[year(coal_policy$datetime)>=2018])),
               color="#332288",size=1.5)+
  geom_vline(xintercept = as.POSIXct(as.Date("2018-01-01")),color="#999933",linetype="dashed")+
  annotate("text", x = as.POSIXct(as.Date("2018-01-01")), y = 5200,
           label = "CCIR\nstarts\nJan 2018",family="Gill Sans MT",
           hjust=-.1,size=3.5)+
  scale_y_continuous(expand=c(0,0),limits=c(0,6000))+
  scale_x_datetime(date_labels="%Y",
                   breaks=breaks.index,
                   limits=c(as.POSIXct(as.Date("2000-01-01")),as.POSIXct(as.Date("2019-01-01"))))+
  theme_economist()+
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill="#CCCCCC"),
        plot.background = element_rect(fill="#CCCCCC"),
        panel.grid.major.y = element_line(size=.2),
        text=element_text(family="Gill Sans MT"))+
  labs(y="",x="",title="Coal power and the effect of policy in Alberta",
       subtitle="Daily average coal generation (MWh)")

topplot

4. Now create a function to make each of the 3 sub-plots

This function takes as arguments:

  • province (for when I was using this on multiple provinces)
  • chart title *chart subtitle
  • and type to specify coal, demand or prices

5. Now create the 3 sub-plots and combine them

AB.coal <- make_plot("AB","coal","Coal is down","Monthly average generation (MWh)")
AB.demand <- make_plot("AB","load","Demand is up","Monthly average demand (MWh)")
AB.price <- make_plot("AB","price","Price responds...","$ per MWh")

# create a common legend
AB.legend <- AB.price + theme(legend.position = "bottom")
g_legend<-function(a.gplot){
  tmp <- ggplot_gtable(ggplot_build(a.gplot))
  leg <- which(sapply(tmp$grobs, function(x) x$name) == "guide-box")
  legend <- tmp$grobs[[leg]]
  return(legend)}
mylegend<-g_legend(AB.legend)

6. Combine all plots

# combine subplots with common legend, add caption
subplots <- grid.arrange(AB.coal,AB.demand,AB.price,nrow=1)

comboplot <- grid.arrange(arrangeGrob(topplot,subplots,ncol=1,heights=c(1.8,1)),
                          mylegend,nrow=2,heights=c(18,1),
                          bottom=textGrob("Data source: AESO (accessed via NRGSTREAM). Chart by @bcshaffer \nSource code available at github.com/blakeshaffer/macleans2019 ",
                                          gp=gpar(fontsize=10,fontfamily="Gill Sans"),
                                          hjust=1,
                                          x=1))
# color entire canvas background grey
comboplot_w_caption <- grid.draw(grobTree(rectGrob(gp=gpar(fill="#CCCCCC", lwd=0)), comboplot))
